    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1925-07-27T04:16:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1925-07-27T04:16:00-05:00" n="119"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d119">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">800.51 W 89Rumania/79: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Chargé in Rumania</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Riggs</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Paraphrase]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Bucharest</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1925-07-27T11:00:00+01:44">
                            <hi rend="italic">July 27, 1925—11 a.m.</hi>
                        </date>
                        <lb/>[Received July 28—12:57 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>67. Mr. Culbertson arrived July 25.<note n="70" xml:id="d119fn70">Because of the
                        King’s absence, Mr. Culbertson was unable to present his letters of credence
                        and Mr. Riggs continued to act as Chargé.</note> He wishes the following
                    communicated to the Department: <quote rend="blockquote">
                        <p>Does the Department wish to press for definite proposal for funding of
                            the Rumanian relief debt in accordance with telegraphic instructions No.
                            13, March 17, 7 p.m., and No. 22, April 9, 1 p.m., or is the oral
                            communication made to Mr. Riggs by the Rumanian Government reported in
                            Legation’s telegram No. 66, July 21, 6 p.m., regarded as satisfactory
                            reply and as transferring the negotiations to Washington on the same
                            basis as the war debts of other nations? I should like to receive
                            instructions whether I can render Department any service by remaining in
                            Bucharest until the King returns or whether I should proceed to Geneva
                            for conference with Minister of Finance Bratiano. The King is not
                            expected to return for four or five weeks.</p>
                    </quote>
                </p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Riggs</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
